## REVISIONS MAPPING

When proposing revisions, use the following templates tailored to issue category:

Language — promissory/superlative:
- Replace absolute claims ("best", "guaranteed", "always outperforms") with qualified alternatives:
  "has historically demonstrated", "aims to", "seeks to", "has a track record of"
- Remove or qualify certainty language: replace "will" with "aims to" or "may"

Language — vague/ambiguous:
- Replace undefined terms ("sustainable approach", "strong performance") with measurable or defined alternatives
- If substantiation is unavailable, flag as conditional: "If [specific criterion] applies, disclose [specific detail]"

Disclosure — missing risk:
- Add: "Past performance is not a reliable indicator of future results."
- Add: "The value of investments may go down as well as up. You may get back less than you invest."
- If ESG product: Add relevant SFDR article classification and sustainability risk disclosure

Disclosure — unbalanced:
- Add missing counterpoint: if only upside is presented, add a balanced risk statement
- If one scenario presented, add: "This scenario is not the only possible outcome."

Performance — misleading / missing assumptions:
- Add: time period, starting date, benchmark used, whether gross or net of fees, currency
- Add standard disclaimer: "Past performance is not indicative of future performance."

Performance — insufficient substantiation:
- The claim lacks supporting data, source, or methodology. Add: the data source, 
  measurement period, and basis of calculation.
- Template: "Substantiate with: [source], covering [period], calculated on a [gross/net] basis."
- If substantiation is unavailable, revise the claim to be qualified: 
  replace assertive language with "based on [available data]" or "as at [date]".

ESG — greenwashing risk:
- Replace unsubstantiated sustainability claim with SFDR-aligned language
- Add: SFDR product classification (Art. 6, 8, or 9), principal adverse impact disclosure reference

Cross-border — jurisdictional ambiguity:
- Add: "This communication is directed only at persons in [jurisdiction]. It is not directed at persons in [excluded jurisdiction]."

Disclosure — incomplete:
- Identify what specific required element is missing (e.g., fees, risks, product classification)
- Use conditional template: "If applicable, add: [specific required disclosure]"
- Do not invent specific values; flag the absence and specify the category of missing information

Market abuse — potential signal:
- Do not propose a direct "rewrite" for market abuse signals; instead suggest process controls:
  "Review this communication against insider list records before release."
  "If inside information may be involved, consult compliance before further distribution."
  "Consider whether a STOR filing obligation is triggered."

